STOP A/B Testing Your YouTube Titles (Do This Instead)

to me


One of the biggest questions people ask about YouTube is:


"Should I A/B test my titles?"

 
Download


Straight-up answer? No.


Here's why: 


If you're relying on YouTube SEO (which you should be, if you're in B2B or educational content)


Changing your title screws up your rankings because YouTube's algorithm relies on engagement metrics like: how many people click, how long they watch and how many stick around


When you switch up titles, you mess with those metrics, which makes it harder for YouTube to understand your video's relevance and rank it properly.


So what should you A/B test? Thumbnails.


Let me break down how we A/B test thumbnails on my channel:


1. Start with a strong baseline.

Choose a design or style that you think will interest your target audience the best. This becomes your control in the A/B testing process.


2. Pick your variables to test.

Here are the elements you're going to focus on:


Text vs. No Text: Some thumbnails work great with text on them, while others perform better without it. It's worth testing both to see what works best.


Numbers on the Thumbnail: Should you include numbers, like a dollar amount or a percentage? For me, we've found that adding something like "$100K" or "5 Tips" increases curiosity + clicks.


Facial Expressions: My face is all over my thumbnails. But which expression works best? Surprised, smiling, serious? It all matters. We test different facial expressions to see which draws the most clicks.


Colors: Color schemes can make or break a thumbnail. We experiment with bright, contrasting colors vs. more muted tones to see what catches the eye.


Simplified vs. Complex: Sometimes a cleaner, simpler thumbnail performs better, and sometimes a more detailed one wins. You won't know until you test it.


3. Use YouTube's Native A/B Testing Tool.

Pro Tip: A lot of people don't know this, but YouTube has its own A/B testing tool for thumbnails. It lets you swap thumbnails and tracks their performance to see which one does better.


Now this is another crucial part of this How long should I A/B test?


You need enough data to make a decision, but you don't want to wait too long and miss out on potential improvements.


The length of time you run your test depends entirely on your channel size:


Large Channels (100k+ views per video)

If you're getting over 100,000 views in the first day, you can A/B test up to NINE different thumbnails in under 24 hours.


Smaller Channels

If you're only getting 1,000 views per video, stick to testing just two thumbnails at a time. This will give you enough data to see which performs better, but it'll take about a week to reach a statistically big enough result.


This Thumbnail A/B Test System of ours has generated 25,000,000+ views for our channel alone.


Yeah, thank me later, ok?


Remember, your title might hook your audience, but your thumbnail is what gets them in the door.


The quicker you figure out what thumbnails work for your audience, the faster you'll see your views (and your YouTube business) grow.



The thumbnail guy, 

Shane
